    <h1>Not much green left after prun&#xAD;ing of trees</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200917/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-17"><time>2020-09-17</time></a>
        - <span>FORUM</span>
        - <span role="byline">Aru&#xAD;mugam Ma&#xAD;niam</span>
    </section>

    <p>I read with be­wil­der­ment the Gov­ern­ment’s ini­tia­tive in “green­ing” the coun­try (In­ten­si­fy­ing green drive and get­ting Sin­ga­pore­ans to be stew­ards of na­ture, Sept 14).</p>
    <p>Why be­wil­der­ment? Just take a look around at the trees after prun­ing. You can hardly see any branches with leaves.</p>
    <p>What is left is the trunk with a few shoots and leaves.</p>
    <p>An­other thing, most neigh­bour­hood up­grad­ing in­volves ce­ment­ing and con­vert­ing grass patches to add chairs and such un­der and around the trees.</p>


